    <li><strong>Flush your pipes</strong> by running cold water for 30 seconds to 2 minutes before drinking, especially in the morning.</li>
    <li><strong>Use cold water only</strong> for drinking and cooking — hot water dissolves more lead from plumbing.</li>
    <li><strong>Install an NSF 53 certified filter</strong> on your primary drinking water source. Even a $10 Amazon Basics pitcher filter provides certified lead protection.</li>
    <li><strong>Replace old faucets</strong> manufactured before 2014 — they may contain up to 8% lead in brass components.</li>
    <li><strong>Check your service line</strong> — contact your water utility to determine if your home is connected by a lead service line. Many utilities maintain databases of known lead lines.</li>
  </ol>

